After having alayzed the data, I decided to choose these indicators: - Proportion of seats held by women in national parliaments (%) ——- SG.GEN.PARL.ZS - Gross enrolment ratio, secondary, gender parity index (GPI) ——- SE.ENR.SECO.FM.ZS - Adolescent fertility rate (births per 1,000 women ages 15-19) ——- SP.ADO.TFRT

Vectors for each country with all the years (1960 to 2015)

year <- sqldf('select distinct Year from world_indicators')
gender_ESP <- data.frame(year)
gender_USA <- data.frame(year)
gender_IND <- data.frame(year)
gender_FRA <- data.frame(year)
gender_CHN <- data.frame(year)
gender_WLD <- data.frame(year)

For the observations that we don´t have data, we do Kalman Smoothing on structural time series models (or on the state space representation of an arima model) for imputation.

  1. Presence of women in parliaments 1.1 Spain
parliaments <- sqldf('select Year, Value from ESP_indicators where IndicatorCode == "SG.GEN.PARL.ZS"')
parliaments_na <- rep(NA, 56)
i <- 1
for (year in parliaments$Year){
  parliaments_na[(year-1960+1)] <- parliaments$Value[i]
  i = i + 1
}
parliaments_ts <- ts(data = parliaments_na, start = 1960, end = 2015, frequency = 1)
if(anyNA(parliaments_ts)){
    parliaments_kalman <- na.kalman(parliaments_ts)
} else{
    parliaments_kalman <- parliaments_ts
}
gender_ESP$'seats held by women in national parliaments (%)' <- parliaments_kalman
plotNA.imputations(parliaments_ts, parliaments_kalman, main = "Women in Parliament ESP")

1.2 USA

parliaments <- sqldf('select Year, Value from USA_indicators where IndicatorCode == "SG.GEN.PARL.ZS"')
parliaments_na <- rep(NA, 56)
i <- 1
for (year in parliaments$Year){
  parliaments_na[(year-1960+1)] <- parliaments$Value[i]
  i = i + 1
}
parliaments_ts <- ts(data = parliaments_na, start = 1960, end = 2015, frequency = 1)
if(anyNA(parliaments_ts)){
    parliaments_kalman <- na.kalman(parliaments_ts)
} else{
    parliaments_kalman <- parliaments_ts
}
gender_USA$'seats held by women in national parliaments (%)' <- parliaments_kalman
plotNA.imputations(parliaments_ts, parliaments_kalman, main = "Women in Parliament USA")

ARIMA FIT (SPAIN)

# response time series stationary?
adf.test(gender_ESP$`seats held by women in national parliaments (%)`)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  gender_ESP$`seats held by women in national parliaments (%)`
## Dickey-Fuller = -1.572, Lag order = 3, p-value = 0.7472
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
gender_stationary <- diff(gender_ESP$`seats held by women in national parliaments (%)`, differences = 1)
plot(gender_stationary)

life.train <- gender_stationary[1:51]
life.test <- gender_stationary[52:55]

#fit ARIMA model
arima.fit <- auto.arima(life.train, stationary = TRUE, seasonal = FALSE)
summary(arima.fit)
## Series: life.train 
## ARIMA(0,0,0) with non-zero mean

##                        ME     RMSE       MAE  MPE MAPE     MASE      ACF1
